For a bursty 10k/min workload, the choice isn't just about the syntax; it’s about whether you want to manage queue throughput as a database scaling problem or an architectural isolation problem.

Postgres `SKIP LOCKED` is a powerful, low-overhead pattern for modest volumes, but as [this deep dive on job drains](https://brandur.org/job-drain) highlights, it directly couples your job processing health to your primary database's lock contention. At 10k events per minute, your database becomes the bottleneck for the queue itself, and you risk spiraling performance degradation when things back up—the exact opposite of what a buffer is supposed to do. Managed queues like SQS offload that pressure by isolating your workers from your DB, but you inherit the complexity of managing "in-flight" limits and visibility timeouts, which the [AWS Builder's Library on backlogs](https://aws.amazon.com/builders-library/avoiding-insurmountable-queue-backlogs/) explains in detail.

```sdanswer
{ "type": "tradeoff", "title": "Postgres Queue vs. Managed Queue", "options": [
  { "label": "Postgres (SKIP LOCKED)", "bullets": [ "Single-stack simplicity", "Transactional atomicity", "High DB contention risk", "Vacuum/bloat management overhead" ] },
  { "label": "Managed (SQS)", "bullets": [ "Total architectural isolation", "Infinite scale (effectively)", "Distributed system complexity", "Visibility timeout management" ] }
] }
```

Regardless of your path, you are implementing a "competing consumers" pattern; [this walkthrough](https://www.rabbitmq.com/tutorials/tutorial-two-python) is the best way to understand how that pattern forces you to think about message acknowledgment and what happens when a worker crashes mid-task. Before you commit to either, ask your team: if your throughput spikes by 5x tomorrow, is the database the piece of infrastructure you want to be troubleshooting under fire?

For a bursty 10k events/minute workload, you should default to a managed queue like SQS rather than building your own on top of Postgres.

While `SKIP LOCKED` is an elegant way to handle queues within a relational database, it is prone to performance degradation as contention scales. As noted in [Transactionally Staged Job Drains in Postgres](https://brandur.org/job-drain), the primary risk is that as your database experiences load, the time it takes for workers to find and lock jobs increases, creating a feedback loop that can throttle your entire database—not just the queue. If you use Postgres for this, you’re also fighting the "transactional trap," where workers start processing jobs before the enclosing transaction has actually committed.

Managed queues like SQS offload that locking and retry logic entirely. They handle bursts gracefully and isolate your database from the churn of job status updates. The trade-off is architectural: you move from a transactional, local-state model to an "at-least-once" delivery model, which means your application code *must* be idempotent, as [Work Queues](https://www.rabbitmq.com/tutorials/tutorial-two-python) explains.

```sdanswer
{
  "type": "tradeoff",
  "title": "Postgres SKIP LOCKED vs. Managed SQS",
  "options": [
    {
      "label": "Postgres SKIP LOCKED",
      "bullets": [
        "Simple, unified schema",
        "Strong ACID guarantees",
        "High locking contention risk",
        "Tied to DB throughput"
      ]
    },
    {
      "label": "Managed SQS",
      "bullets": [
        "Scales independently of DB",
        "Built-in burst handling",
        "At-least-once complexity",
        "Requires idempotent workers"
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

If you decide to go with SQS, pay close attention to the [in-flight message limits and visibility timeouts](https://aws.amazon.com/builders-library/avoiding-insurmountable-queue-backlogs/) mentioned in the AWS Builders Library; that’s where the most common operational bugs in queue-based systems hide. Regardless of which you choose, the real hurdle isn't the enqueueing—it's ensuring your consumer logic doesn't choke when the service that *receives* the message slows down.

Go with **SQS** if your priority is surviving the 10k/min bursts without manual scaling; go with **Postgres SKIP LOCKED** only if you strictly need atomic job creation (the job and the data that triggered it must be saved together or not at all).

At 10,000 events per minute, Postgres starts to feel the friction of a "competing consumers" model. As explained in [Transactionally Staged Job Drains in Postgres](https://brandur.org/job-drain), the "frantic pace" at which workers try to lock rows can degrade performance under heavy load, potentially leading to a queue spiral if transactions run long. You also face the "visibility race": a fast worker might try to pick up a job before the transaction that created it has actually committed, causing immediate, avoidable failures.

SQS is built for exactly this "bursty" profile. In [Avoiding insurmountable queue backlogs](https://aws.amazon.com/builders-library/avoiding-insurmountable-queue-backlogs/), Amazon describes using "surge queues" and visibility timeouts to handle massive spikes without falling over. However, you must design your workers for "at-least-once" delivery—if a worker crashes before deleting the message, SQS will eventually hand it to another worker. This means your job processing must be idempotent, a pattern outlined in the [RabbitMQ Work Queues tutorial](https://www.rabbitmq.com/tutorials/tutorial-two-python).

