}
```

If you choose Postgres, your next challenge will be tuning `autovacuum` to handle the high-churn "delete-as-you-go" pattern typical of database queues.

Think of the transactional outbox as an **application-level decision** (you explicitly write your intent to send an email) and CDC as an **infrastructure-level observation** (you passively record that state changed).

The [Transactional outbox](https://microservices.io/patterns/data/transactional-outbox.html) pattern is your best bet when you need strict "intent" control. Because your email agent needs to trigger a specific action (sending an email) that must succeed if and only if the business transaction commits, staging that "email intent" in an outbox table ensures atomic consistency. This [staged job](https://brandur.org/job-drain) approach keeps the email work invisible until the transaction finishes, so you never accidentally fire off an email for a transaction that rolls back.

CDC is better when you want to stream raw state changes to downstream services without tightly coupling your application code to those events. If you use CDC, you are essentially asking your database to emit events based on what happened, rather than asking your code to emit events based on what it *intended* to do.

```sdanswer
{
  "type": "tradeoff",
  "title": "Outbox vs. CDC",
  "options": [
    {
      "label": "Transactional Outbox",
      "bullets": [
        "Explicitly defines event intent",
        "Couples code to event schema",
        "Zero extra infrastructure required"
      ]
    },
    {
      "label": "Change Data Capture (CDC)",
      "bullets": [
        "Captures raw state transitions",
        "Decoupled from application logic",
        "Requires dedicated infrastructure"
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

Since both patterns are inherently "at-least-once" delivery mechanisms—the relay process might crash and restart after publishing an event—your consumer must handle idempotency. Before you ship, verify that your email-sending service tracks processed message IDs, or your users will eventually receive the same "agentic" notification twice.

Start with [Use The Index, Luke!](https://use-the-index-luke.com/); it’s the most effective way to build a vendor-agnostic mental model of B-trees and index traversal before you dive into storage engine specifics. While many devs treat indexes as magic "go-fast" buttons, this resource treats them as balanced tree structures you can reason about, which is the necessary foundation for understanding why certain queries scale and others crawl.

Once you have the indexing primitives down, you need to bridge the gap between "how data is stored" and "how data is safely modified." Understanding transactional isolation—the idea that uncommitted changes remain invisible to other workers—is your entry point into Multi-Version Concurrency Control (MVCC). [Transactionally Staged Job Drains in Postgres](https://brandur.org/job-drain) provides a fantastic concrete example of this by showing how ACID properties keep staged jobs invisible until a `COMMIT` is issued.

