As you work through these, keep an eye on the "Write-Ahead Log" (WAL) concept: it's the mechanism that ensures your B-tree updates survive a crash even before they're fully flushed to the main data files.

You need to treat each agentic loop iteration as a nested child span within your existing distributed trace, using OpenTelemetry to ensure the tool call activity links back to the original production request.

A runaway loop is effectively an agent "wrecking its environment" until it hits a terminal state, as described in [Designing agentic loops](https://simonwillison.net/2025/Sep/30/designing-agentic-loops/). To debug this, propagate your parent trace context into the agent's tool-execution layer. Using [Distributed Tracing with Better Stack](https://betterstack.com/docs/logs/tracing/) or any OTLP-compliant backend, you can then visualize the request flow end-to-end. This approach allows you to jump from a high-level trace directly to the logs and metrics for the specific iteration that went rogue, letting you see the exact input/output that caused the agent to loop rather than terminate.

Before you wire this up, implement a hard iteration limit or a circuit breaker inside your agent loop; tracing will show you exactly *why* it's looping, but it won't stop the agent from burning through your API budget or rate limits while you're still debugging.

